				<td>&nbsp;</td><td>Re: The Importance of Stats</td></tr>
			<tr>
				<td class="msg_user_cell" width="200" valign=top>
				
					<span style='color:#6600CC;'>Lluianae</span> <img src='http://starwarsgalaxies.station.sony.com/images/forum_images/holiday_c/wreath_a.gif' border=0 alt=''> 
					<br>
					
						Philosopher
						
					<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
					







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Races/high_elf.jpg" border=0 alt=""/>
					<br>
					
				</td>
				<td rowspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" style="text-align: justify;" width="100%" valign=top>
				<div></div><div></div>CLASS: (True Battle) Cleric, highest end raider, double marker of Ayonae! (Magelo in Sig)<br>

<div>&nbsp;</div>

<div>HP: Very Important. For groups and raids it reflects how many hits
one can take from loose adds until a tank can recover / take aggro to
prevent you from dieing, also key to harsh DoTs, AE DDs and detrimental
AEs that reduce the hp cap by a significant amount, as it will scale.
For soloing, it affects the rate of healing required by allowing a
cleric to delay using bigger more efficient heals, over using smaller,
less efficient ones. It also means the max number of bad potential
rounds a cleric can take, whilst tanking, taking hits, or soloing (as
it does for all classes), but considering our evasion is so poor, we
need as big a limit as we can, for our class.<br>
<br>Mana:&nbsp; Very Important. Mana is the literal lifeblood for our
class, we are completely dependant on it for doing our job as a whole
class (clickies that a minority have access to shouldn't be factored
into that), and what with increasing mana drains and harsh damage
needing to be countered that people are facing in raids / groups (mana
drains less so, mana sponges thats another matter <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-tongue.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>), having an ample
supply of mana is key. That said, managing mana efficiently &gt; a
super high mana pool, but more often than not true efficiency is nigh
impossible to achieve- a drain is bound to happen.<br>
<br>Endurance: Useless, only used for jumping <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-tongue.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br>
<br>AC: Biased to say important. Clerics are a plate class, and it is
intended for us to have a good mitigation source from our AC, such that
after parsing from the cleric community, we proved our post soft-cap AC
return was severely broken, and Zajeer checked and saw it wasn't what
it was intended to be. He fixed that, and much &lt;3 for the iksar SK,
because now our AC has worth. Being a cleric with one of the highest ac
values unbuffed serverwide for my class (and a decent shield AC to go with it) I can
safely say that AC has saved my ass more times than I can count in
raids and grouping. It is also key again, to the solo aspect for
clerics, because our dps relies on us getting hit / being attacked, and
considering our evasion is poor being a priest class, we need to do
everything we can to minimise damage taken whilst in return, still
doing damage back.<br>
 </div>

<div>&nbsp;</div>

<div>HP Regen: So so. Being a healer, HP regen worn is not that
important to me as I am capable of regenning HP via my heals in HoTs or
Direct Burst heals.<br>
<br>Mana Regen: Important. Clerics are the worst off of all priests
when it comes to mana regen, but this is primarily due to our heals
being the more comparitively totally efficient in terms of Average Heal
per Mana Second, and due to the fact we have the heal of CH which has
often been the crux of many issues / debates, however I can safely say
the dusk of CH has already started, as there are several heals already
better suited than CH, with the appropriate foci.<br>
<br>Endurance Regen: Useless, but give it to melees, they DIRELY need it <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br>
<br>
 </div>

<div>&nbsp;<br>
Stats in general- people can cap stats quite easily in general these
days especially if they raid, so I would not be too concerned with them
all overal.<br>
<br>
</div>

<div>Strength: Semi-important, being a plate class our armour is heavy. We don't need to be encumbered <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br>
<br>Stamina: Important until capped, it provides the a needed boost of hp.<br>
<br>Agility:
So so, it affects AGI avoidance AC and supposedly affects the proc
rates of defensive parry proccers, of which our primary solo tool now,
is one (ward of retribution).<br>
<br>Dexterity: Again like Agi, it affects
the proc rate of weapons marginally? Which one of our tools is the set
of spam0matic hammers.<br>
<br>Charisma: Not that important.<br>
<br>Intelligence: Not important.<br>
<br>Wisdom: Important to the class as a whole, but wisdom is easy to
cap for most of the population these days. If it provided a post cap
return based mana / x amount of wisdom, akin to how AC works, it would
make wisdom more appreciated, as many people are hundreds above the cap.<br>
 </div>

<div>&nbsp;<br>
Well, despite the fact most AEs&nbsp; in raids have checks that
completely negate the benefit of resists, meaning merely a resist
depends on the roll of a too many sided dice, of which the sucess would
be the Vishimtar DoN resist aa. In general however, I deem them
important, I have faith in resists, such that I have once resisted most
AEs mata muram has had to throw at me, and am thankful it happened
(Silence resisted, Gaze emote... &gt;&lt<img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-wink.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br>
<br>
</div>

<div>Cold Resist: Semi important.<br>Disease Resist: Semi important.<br>Poison Resist: Semi important.<br>Magic Resist: Semi important.<br>Fire Resist: Semi important. </div>

<div>&nbsp;<br>
Clerics are the least dependant on melee weapons, our melee dps is appaling, but we derive most of our dps via defensive means.<br>
<br>
</div>

<div>Attack: Not important<br>Delay: Not important<br>Damage: Not important<br>Range: Not important </div>

<div>Haste: Not important- haste doesn't increase proc rate, with haste our melee dps hardly rises, we miss too much anyways.<br>
<br>
"Addition" Proc: Important- our spam hammer line is one of our 'dps'
means, however, the hammers are not the dps people expect them to be
even with their proc rate. The best hammer currently (Daybreak, Bringer
of Light) parses at 30-35 burst dps with crit aa's, 20-25 dps in normal
settings. A slight boost on them would be a nice thing, as we are one
of if not the most dps challenged classes in the game.<br>
 </div>

<div>&nbsp;<br>
<br>
</div>

<div>Combat Effects: So so, useful on weapons with timelapse, but not with spam hammers that already have the 630% mod proc rate.<br>
<br>Shielding: Important, shielding is useful to everyone, and especially us for soloing reasons (see above for ac)<br>
<br>Stun Resist: Important, but a bit bleh being sketchy as it is RNG
based on whether you stun resist or not, useful in all areas of EQ
however.<br>
<br>Strikethrough: Useless, ST does not avoid ripostes but it merely
bypasses them, our melee dps is too low for this to be a concern.<br>
<br>Spell Shield: Important. Spell shield is the single biggest
mitigator for spell damage, such that it exponentially scales as DD
base increases, saving far more hps than people care to admit <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br>
<br>Avoidance: Important. Priests in general get hit by mobs for a
hitrate of 60%, with capped avoidance this shifts to ~50%, which is a
huge dps cutdown. Evasion &gt; mitigation for surviving, not being hit
at all is a great thing. That said, very easy to max now.<br>
<br>Accuracy: Not important. We miss too much base without accuracy, an
improvement in 1-2% hitrate will hardly do much for ~10 melee dps.<br>
<br>DOT Shielding: Important as again it is a fixed benefit / tick
but... its way way too abundant in comparison to other mods. I think
there are people with even 70+% lol.<br>
 </div>

<div>&nbsp;</div>

Skill Mods: Specialisation Alt 12% is an example of a great skill mod
that people place not so much worth in. It is a fixed additional 1%
mana preservation to alteration spells, assuming Alt Speci is capped at
200. +dodge % or others like that, are not so useful for clerics,
because our innate dodge skill is capped at a low 80.<br>
<br>
Click Effects: &lt;3 &lt;3 &lt;3 clickies, my bank and bags are full of
them, useful and useless, I just love em <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0> I really do have too much
though... &gt;&lt;<br>
<br>
Proc Effects:&nbsp; See above<br>
<br>
Worn Effects: If this counts worn DS then I say yes, it is quite
important, because DS is critical for any efficient damage when a
cleric solos, we do more damage over a long period of time with damage
shields and marks, than we ever do with ward. Improved Dodge is decent,
its not a huge huge benefit, but its still decent. Cleave is fun but
its not that useful <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-tongue.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0><br>
<br>
Focus Effects: IMPORTANT. Casters are extremely dependant on foci to
achieve their best / average performances with their spells. However,
currently, foci are at the most 1-65%, which is a 1/65 chance of
hitting any of the numbers. This is a large dice to roll, and makes us
very dependant on RNG, even with foci that are at the most 40%. The way
to alleviate this in general, whilst still being an upgrade, would be
to produce items with foci that have a raised minimum from 1%. It
reduces the amount of values RNG can pick, whilst raising the average,
improving average sustainability of heals, dots nukes and so forth.
Other than that, I am happy with the progression of all other foci.<br><br>
<br>
Hope this helps Merloc <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>
